SIMPLE: swell
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Swell
<hw>Swell</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos>
<conjf>Swelled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Swelled</conjf> or <conjf>Swollen</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p.
pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Swelling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS.
<ets>swellan</ets>; akin to D. <ets>zwellen</ets>, OS. & OHG.
<ets>swellan</ets>, G. <ets>schwellen</ets>, Icel. <ets>svella</ets>,
Sw. <ets>sv⟦aum⟧lla</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To grow larger; to
dilate or extend the exterior surface or dimensions, by matter added
within, or by expansion of the inclosed substance; <as>as, the legs
<ex>swell</ex> in dropsy; a bruised part <ex>swells</ex>; a bladder
<ex>swells</ex> by inflation.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To increase in size or extent by any addition; to
increase in volume or force; <as>as, a river <ex>swells</ex>, and
overflows its banks; sounds <ex>swell</ex> or diminish.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To rise or be driven into waves or billows; to
heave; <as>as, in tempest, the ocean <ex>swells</ex> into
waves</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To be puffed up or bloated; <as>as, to
<ex>swell</ex> with pride</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You <qex>swell</qex> at the tartan, as the bull is said to do at
scarlet.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To be inflated; to belly; <as>as, the sails
<ex>swell</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To be turgid, bombastic, or extravagant; <as>as,
<ex>swelling</ex> words; a <ex>swelling</ex> style.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To protuberate; to bulge out; <as>as, a cask
<ex>swells</ex> in the middle</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To be elated; to rise arrogantly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your equal mind yet <qex>swells</qex> not into state.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>To grow upon the view; to become larger; to
expand.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Monarchs to behold the <xex>swelling</xex>
scene!⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>To become larger in amount; <as>as, many little
debts added, <ex>swell</ex> to a great amount</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>To act in a pompous, ostentatious, or arrogant
manner; to strut; to look big.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Here he comes, <qex>swelling</qex> like a turkey cock.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swell</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Swell
<hw>Swell</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To increase the size,
bulk, or dimensions of; to cause to rise, dilate, or increase; <as>as,
rains and dissolving snow <ex>swell</ex> the rivers in spring;
immigration <ex>swells</ex> the population</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[The Church] <qex>swells</qex> her high, heart-cheering tone.</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To aggravate; to heighten.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is low ebb with his accuser when such peccadilloes are put to
<qex>swell</qex> the charge.</q> <rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To raise to arrogance; to puff up; to inflate;
<as>as, to be <ex>swelled</ex> with pride or haughtiness</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>To augment gradually in force or
loudness, as the sound of a note.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swell</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Swell
<hw>Swell</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
swelling.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Gradual increase.</def> Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd>
<def>Increase or augmentation in bulk; protuberance.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>Increase in height; elevation; rise.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Little River affords navigation during a <qex>swell</qex> to
within three miles of the Miami.</q> <rj><qau>Jefferson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>Increase of force, intensity, or volume of
sound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Music arose with its voluptuous <qex>swell</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <def>Increase of power in style, or of rhetorical
force.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>swell</qex> and subsidence of his periods.</q>
<rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A gradual ascent, or rounded elevation, of land;
<as>as, an extensive plain abounding with little
<ex>swells</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A wave, or billow; especially, a succession of large
waves; the roll of the sea after a storm; <as>as, a heavy <ex>swell</ex>
sets into the harbor</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>swell</qex>⟦br⟧
Of the long waves that roll in yonder bay.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The gigantic <qex>swells</qex> and billows of the snow.</q>
<rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A gradual increase and decrease of
the volume of sound; the crescendo and diminuendo combined; -- generally
indicated by the sign.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A showy, dashing person; a dandy.</def>
<mark>[Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Ground swell</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Ground</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Organ swell</b></col>
<fld>(Mus.)</fld>, <cd>a certain number of pipes inclosed in a box, the
uncovering of which by means of a pedal produces increased sound.</cd>
-- <col><b>Swell shark</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a small shark
(<spn>Scyllium ventricosum</spn>) of the west coast of North America,
which takes in air when caught, and swells up like a
swellfish.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swell</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Swell
<hw>Swell</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Having the characteristics of a
person of rank and importance; showy; dandified; distinguished; <as>as,
a <ex>swell</ex> person; a <ex>swell</ex> neighborhood.</as></def>
<mark>[Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Swell mob</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Mob</er>.</cd>
<mark>[Slang]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swelldom</ent>⟦br⟧
